The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, August 21, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 Scicom Infotech plans to scale up operations by hiring 100 professionals more by next year-end and setting up a new facility in Noida for which the company will go for another r ound of funding to raise $3 million. At present, there are 200 workers and a development centre each in Noida and the US.																								 UTStarcom Inc, a US-based IP access networking major, has bagged a $8.2-million contract from BSNL for its national internet backbone project. UTStarcom will deploy its Total Control 1000 multiservice access platform and related equipment for the second phase of BSNLs national internet backbone.																								 Upper Ganges Sugar and Industries Ltd has recorded a turnover of Rs 263.07 crore for the year ended June 30. Operating profit stood at Rs 58.82 crore against Rs 16.93 crore in 2002-03. Profit before tax stood at Rs 27.75 crore against a loss of Rs 10.72 crore in the previous year, registering a growth of over 300 per cent.																								 Bandhan, a development and training institute, started its micro finance activity in 2002 with technical input from ASA, a Bangladesh-based micro finance institution, and financial assistance from Sidbi. ASA-Bandhan has achieved a 500 per cent growth last fiscal and has disbursed Rs 2.98 crore in five districts of Bengal.																								 The board of Helios amp; Matheson Information Technology has proposed a bonus issue in the ratio of one share for every one held. The bonus shares will be issued after obtaining shareholders approval at an annual general meeting on September 28.																								 Acer India has established a volume product division to capture the growing small and medium enterprises and SOHO segments. The firm has also launched Acer Power S200 and Acer Power S100 priced at Rs 18,999 and Rs 20,999, respectively.																								 Mahindra British Telecom (MBT), a leading independent IT services provider for the telecom industry, and RateIntegration Inc, a rating software solutions provider, have entered into a pact to provide enhanced rating and specialised integration capabilities to the global telecom firms.																								 Blue dart Express Limited, a courier and logistics company, has launched Rakhee Express, a service to deliver rakhees in specially designed envelopes. The offer is available in Mumbai, Delhi, Bangalore, Calcutta and Pune.																								 Graphite India Ltd, the flagship of the Calcutta-based K. K. Bangur group, has completed the acquisition of the Germany-based Conradty group for 11.3 million euro. ADVERTISEMENT
